  "answer": "The critic’s charge of an ad hoc exclusion fails because the scope of the mechanism is explicitly limited to polities whose administrative systems were built on a specific socio-technical configuration—namely, palace economies dependent on a tightly held, non-alphabetic scribal monopoly (Linear B and related cuneiform traditions) that collapsed when exposed to more diffused, alphabetic accounting practices. The Egyptian New Kingdom was not such a system: its scribal class operated with a different institutional embedding (temple- and state-based, with a more resilient and adaptable hieratic tradition), a different linguistic economy, and a different political ecology that did not make administrative continuity vulnerable to the same phase transition. The forbidden case is therefore not a counterexample to the mechanism as specified; it is a case the mechanism’s scope conditions were never designed to cover. The target’s prose note that Egypt’s survival requires a ‘separate explanation’ is not an ad hoc retreat but a recognition that the mechanism’s boundary conditions—the initial state of the information-structure—were not met there. The standard for a forbidden case is that it be a concrete observation that could falsify the mechanism if the mechanism’s scope conditions are satisfied; since the scope explicitly excludes Egypt, the case does not engage the mechanism and thus cannot falsify it."
